When visible light was employed to excite the photocatalysts, TiO2 shows little ability in decomposing RhB, while TiO2–CQDs(12) can decompose about 77% RhB in 150min (Fig. 5
                     (a)). Even this photoactivity is much lower than that under the UV irradiation, the introduced CQDs indeed open a new way for TiO2 to make sufficient use of the solar energy for environment protection. It is clear that the visible light photocatalytic activity of TiO2–CQDs(12) is almost unchanged after four photocatalytic reaction cycles (Fig. 5(b)), suggesting TiO2–CQDs(12) is very stable under the light irradiation. This is superior to other semiconductor quantum dots, such as CdS, which may cause photocorrosion. Afterwards, the effect of the amount of CQDs on the visible light photocatalytic activities was investigated (Fig. 6
                     ). The degradation efficiency increased gradually with the increased carbon content at the beginning. The application of 12mg sodium citrate for generating CQDs to modify TiO2 exhibited the highest photocatalytic activity for RhB degradation. Then the visible light photocatalytic activity decreased slightly when the sodium citrate reached to 20mg. This may attribute to the shielding effect of carbon-based materials [36]. These results clearly demonstrate that CQDs are very efficient in enhancing the photocatalytic activity of TiO2. However, the exact molar ratio of CQDs to TiO2 cannot be calculated based on the photocatalytic film. Further work is need when the TiO2 is used for practical application.
